00:44.411 --> 00:47.869
<i>Some people hear their own
inner voices...</i>

00:47.948 --> 00:49.677
<i>with great clearness...</i>

00:49.750 --> 00:52.981
<i>and they live
by what they hear.</i>

00:53.053 --> 00:56.147
<i>Such people become crazy...</i>

00:56.223 --> 00:58.487
<i>or they become legend.</i>

01:05.966 --> 01:10.630
<i>Tristan Ludlow was born
in the Moon of the Falling Leaves.</i>

01:10.704 --> 01:13.229
<i>It was a terrible winter.</i>

01:13.307 --> 01:18.301
<i>His mother almost died
bringing him into this world.</i>

01:22.149 --> 01:26.017
<i>His father, the Colonel,
brought him to me.</i>

01:26.086 --> 01:31.251
<i>I wrapped him in a bearskin
and held him all that night.</i>

01:33.761 --> 01:35.695
<i>As he grew into a man...</i>

01:35.763 --> 01:39.199
<i>I taught him the great joy
of the kill...</i>

01:39.266 --> 01:42.030
<i>when the hunter
cuts out its warm heart...</i>

01:42.102 --> 01:45.094
<i>and holds it in his hands...</i>

01:45.172 --> 01:48.164
<i>setting its spirit free.</i>

01:50.210 --> 01:52.701
<i>Colonel Ludlow had three sons...</i>

01:52.780 --> 01:56.341
<i>but Tristan was his favorite.</i>

01:56.417 --> 01:58.442
<i>I had had sons, too.</i>

02:00.321 --> 02:02.255
<i>But they were gone now...</i>

02:02.323 --> 02:03.756
<i>forever.</i>

02:05.092 --> 02:08.220
<i>It was a very bad time.</i>

02:08.294 --> 02:11.658
<i>The Colonel had tried
to help the people...</i>

02:13.967 --> 02:17.368
<i>but it was no use.</i>

02:17.438 --> 02:21.101
<i>So he decided
to go his own way.</i>

02:23.544 --> 02:27.708
<i>He wanted to lose the madness
over the mountains, he said...</i>

02:27.781 --> 02:29.874
<i>and begin again.</i>

02:37.991 --> 02:40.459
<i>"Lose the madness," he said.</i>

02:40.527 --> 02:43.325
<i>And so we lived for many years...</i>

02:43.397 --> 02:45.262
<i>and the boys grew strong.</i>

02:55.042 --> 02:58.273
<i>Alfred was the older brother...</i>

02:58.345 --> 03:00.404
<i>old even for his years.</i>

03:01.949 --> 03:04.918
<i>Samuel was the youngest.</i>

03:04.985 --> 03:08.318
<i>There was nothing these brothers
would not do for him.</i>

03:08.389 --> 03:10.823
<i>They watched over him
like a treasure.</i>

03:12.593 --> 03:14.026
<i>One year...</i>

03:14.094 --> 03:17.757
<i>I am an old man,
cannot remember the year...</i>

03:17.831 --> 03:20.823
<i>But it was the Moon
of the Red Grass...</i>

03:20.901 --> 03:23.597
<i>when Isabel Ludlow,
their mother...</i>

03:23.670 --> 03:25.831
<i>went away for the winter.</i>

03:25.906 --> 03:29.865
<i>She said the winters
were too cruel for her.</i>

03:29.943 --> 03:32.776
<i>She said she was afraid
of the bears.</i>

03:33.981 --> 03:36.279
<i>She was a strange woman anyway.</i>

03:50.564 --> 03:53.931
<i>That spring, though,
she did not return.</i>

03:55.536 --> 04:00.132
<i>And, after that, she did not
come much to see us.</i>

04:01.341 --> 04:04.310
<i>Alfred wrote her many letters...</i>

04:04.378 --> 04:07.814
<i>but Tristan refused
to speak of her.</i>

04:07.881 --> 04:11.214
<i>His world was here with me.</i>

04:14.188 --> 04:18.716
<i>Every warrior hopes
a good death will find him...</i>

04:18.791 --> 04:20.817
<i>but Tristan couldn't wait.</i>

04:22.062 --> 04:24.155
<i>He went looking for his.</i>

05:43.176 --> 05:45.269
Tristan!

05:45.345 --> 05:46.778
Here

05:50.317 --> 05:52.610
- Was it a bear?
- Yes, sir.

05:52.686 --> 05:54.176
- Can you breathe?
- Yes

05:54.254 --> 05:56.347
Take your hand away.
Take it away!

05:59.526 --> 06:02.120
You're a stupid,
half-brained jackass.

06:02.195 --> 06:04.755
- Yes, sir.
- 'One Stab' put you up to this?

06:06.967 --> 06:08.730
You deserve to be dead,
you know that?

06:08.802 --> 06:10.895
God knows how you've
lived so long.

06:10.971 --> 06:12.905
It'll be all right, son.

06:32.225 --> 06:34.785
<i>I have these letters...</i>

06:34.861 --> 06:37.853
<i>many letters.</i>

06:37.931 --> 06:40.331
<i>Read them.</i>

06:40.400 --> 06:42.334
<i>They are from all of them...</i>

06:43.303 --> 06:45.134
<i>Ludlow...</i>

06:45.205 --> 06:46.934
<i>Isabel...</i>

06:47.007 --> 06:48.872
<i>Samuel...</i>

06:48.942 --> 06:50.603
<i>the whole family...</i>

06:50.677 --> 06:53.441
<i>the whole story...</i>

06:53.513 --> 06:56.607
<i>It is all written here.</i>

06:57.884 --> 07:01.012
<i>"April 13, 1913</i>

07:01.088 --> 07:02.885
<i>Dear Isabel,</i>

07:02.956 --> 07:06.915
<i>I am not fool enough to try
to reorder a life already lived...</i>

07:06.994 --> 07:11.431
<i>but I fear I have not done well raising
our sons alone in this wild place.</i>

07:13.000 --> 07:14.968
<i>What did I know of children?</i>

07:15.035 --> 07:17.629
<i>I was trained to lead men.</i>

07:17.704 --> 07:19.934
<i>This is infinitely harder."</i>

07:21.008 --> 07:22.441
<i>"Dear William,</i>

07:22.509 --> 07:26.240
<i>You take too much responsibility
on yourself, as always.</i>

07:26.313 --> 07:28.941
<i>Our sons are finding their own paths.</i>

07:29.016 --> 07:32.281
<i>They are willful, certainly,
but then...</i>

07:32.352 --> 07:35.515
<i>who are you and I
to complain of willfulness?</i>

07:35.589 --> 07:38.023
<i>As for Samuel,
I have big news.</i>

07:38.091 --> 07:40.025
<i>At a Harvard tea
for Amy Lowell...</i>

07:40.093 --> 07:43.995
<i>he met and instantly loved
Miss Susannah Finncannon.</i>

07:44.064 --> 07:46.862
<i>I know it will
surprise you greatly...</i>

07:46.933 --> 07:49.697
<i>but they are engaged.</i>

07:49.700 --> 07:52.333
<i>He will bring her to Montana
this summer to introduce her...</i>

07:52.334 --> 07:54.540
<i>to his brothers
and to you.</i>

07:54.550 --> 07:57.772
<i>So, William,
please behave yourself...</i>

07:57.844 --> 08:01.905
<i>and be as charming
as only you can be."</i>

08:05.118 --> 08:06.585
There he is!

08:10.557 --> 08:13.117
- How the hell are you?
- Good And you?

08:15.962 --> 08:18.487
- Samuel Good to see you, boy.
- Father, how are you?

08:18.565 --> 08:20.089
- Good to see you.
- Hello.

08:23.338 --> 08:27.763
Oh, uh, father...
This is my fiancÃ©e, Susannah.

08:27.841 --> 08:30.139
- Hello.
- Miss Finncannon.

08:32.245 --> 08:34.611
- Nice to meet you.
- It's an honor.

08:36.149 --> 08:38.275
- This is Alfred.
- How do you do?

08:40.886 --> 08:43.321
- Here's your dog, miss.
- Thank you.

08:43.390 --> 08:46.257
- It's a horse.
- That's a strange-looking animal.

08:46.326 --> 08:49.295
This is Finn.
He's a champion.

08:49.362 --> 08:52.456
You like exotic-looking
dogs then, Miss Finncannon?

08:52.532 --> 08:54.432
Very much, Mr. Ludlow.

08:55.702 --> 08:58.432
- Please, call me Susannah.
- All right.

08:58.505 --> 09:00.996
- He's just plain old Alfred.
- Shut up.

09:01.908 --> 09:06.368
- Where's Tristan?
- He's off somewhere. You know him.

09:06.446 --> 09:09.973
He'll welcome you home tonight
or I'll know the reason why.

09:11.785 --> 09:14.515
Miss Finncannon, please.
Did you have a good journey?

09:20.193 --> 09:22.991
<i>"She is such a lovely creature, William</i>

09:23.063 --> 09:24.963
<i>But I fear the loss
of her parents</i>

09:25.031 --> 09:28.831
<i>has given her
a certain fragility</i>

09:28.902 --> 09:31.837
<i>I think she feels very alone
in the world</i>

09:32.973 --> 09:36.340
<i>But she has found a new family now,
hasn't she?"</i>

09:36.409 --> 09:39.276
The German military is ready
to use chaos in Croatia...

09:39.346 --> 09:43.210
as a justification for actions that could
plunge the entire civilized world into...

09:43.283 --> 09:47.451
Samuel... the word "civilized" has no place
in any discussion of the affairs of this world.

09:47.506 --> 09:49.006
Miss Finncannon.

09:49.256 --> 09:52.692
Mother told us of your sympathy
for the social reformers.

09:53.694 --> 09:56.154
You make it sound like a disease.

09:56.230 --> 09:58.359
No, on the contrary,
I'm in agreement.

09:58.431 --> 10:01.958
You mother told me all about One Stab.
She says he was a great warrior.

10:02.035 --> 10:03.502
Yes.

10:03.570 --> 10:06.061
He has a bag of scalps
to prove it.

10:07.240 --> 10:09.265
But don't worry.

10:09.342 --> 10:11.276
He's devoted to Father now.

10:11.344 --> 10:13.073
Or rather, they're devoted
to each other.

10:13.146 --> 10:14.841
Can he speak English?

10:14.915 --> 10:17.383
Stab, speak English?

10:17.450 --> 10:20.886
He wouldn't lower himself
to speak English. Would you, Stab?

10:22.289 --> 10:25.725
But watch out because
he understands it perfectly well.

10:27.527 --> 10:29.495
There's Tristan.

10:49.382 --> 10:51.577
- Don't they feed you?
- Not much.

10:58.258 --> 11:01.421
- You smell.
- Miss me, did you?

11:01.494 --> 11:03.428
- Still hung over?
- Still drunk.

11:07.734 --> 11:10.225
Isn't she amazing?

11:10.303 --> 11:12.168
So this is Tristan.

11:15.442 --> 11:17.433
And does he speak English?

11:19.646 --> 11:21.113
For God's sake!

11:33.159 --> 11:37.118
Miss Finncannon,
it's a pleasure to meet you.

11:37.197 --> 11:39.961
I hope you and Ugly here...

11:40.033 --> 11:41.830
find every happiness together.

11:46.539 --> 11:50.942
Don't mind my brother. Your dog
has more breeding than he has.

12:14.367 --> 12:16.665
This is Mother's room.

12:16.736 --> 12:18.169
It's lovely.

12:21.875 --> 12:24.070
- It's a pleasure to meet you, Pet.
- And you, miss.

12:24.144 --> 12:25.577
Thank you.

12:34.888 --> 12:37.652
- Which one?
- It's this one.

12:42.629 --> 12:44.563
Angelica Susannah.

13:16.329 --> 13:18.593
Hello.

13:19.599 --> 13:21.362
You must be Isabel Two.

13:25.038 --> 13:27.302
I've already met your mother
and father.

13:29.042 --> 13:30.805
- How old are you?
- Thirteen.

13:35.015 --> 13:38.143
When I was 13,
I was sent away...

13:38.218 --> 13:40.243
to boarding school.

13:41.221 --> 13:42.620
I hated it.

13:44.858 --> 13:46.120
May I help you?

13:50.130 --> 13:51.620
You're going to marry Samuel.

13:51.698 --> 13:53.325
That's right, I am.

13:53.400 --> 13:55.391
I'm going to marry Tristan.

13:58.371 --> 13:59.804
We'll be sisters.

14:01.841 --> 14:04.674
I see you two have met.

14:04.744 --> 14:06.473
Isabel Two is letting me help.

14:06.981 --> 14:10.449
Susannah, would you like to take
a rest? You must be exhausted.

14:10.517 --> 14:12.985
No, not at all.
This is so refreshing...

14:13.053 --> 14:16.989
all this grandeur,
this unexpected...

14:17.057 --> 14:19.321
gift from God.

14:19.392 --> 14:23.692
It doesn't seem like much of a gift
in a hard winter, I assure you.

14:24.597 --> 14:26.189
Where's Samuel?

14:26.266 --> 14:29.599
Inside I could tell your father
wanted him all to himself.

14:30.804 --> 14:34.604
- You're very generous.
- No, just happy.

14:38.678 --> 14:40.771
Stop mooning over her
and come in here.

14:40.847 --> 14:44.544
Samuel wants to know
about those calves from Cheyenne.

14:44.617 --> 14:46.107
Get in here!

14:47.720 --> 14:50.484
Please, excuse my father.

14:50.557 --> 14:55.187
It makes him feel young and powerful
to treat us like we're idiot children.

15:01.134 --> 15:04.900
For all His countless blessings,
may God's holy name be praised. Amen.

15:08.108 --> 15:11.475
Tell Father what you were saying
about Vienna.

15:11.544 --> 15:13.705
- What's that?
- It's the Kaiser.

15:14.948 --> 15:17.473
He won't stop them
from annihilating Serbia.

15:17.550 --> 15:19.575
Let's not talk about war, please.

15:20.553 --> 15:23.818
Susannah hears
that England's mobilizing.

15:23.890 --> 15:26.586
We're stuck out here
while all this is going on.

15:26.659 --> 15:30.390
- Well, thank God for that.
- You wouldn't want us to evade a duty

15:30.463 --> 15:33.432
- Wouldn't I?
- Father, with respect...

15:35.201 --> 15:36.896
Please excuse me
for being late.

15:36.970 --> 15:40.030
I packed so carefully,
I couldn't find anything.

15:41.808 --> 15:44.208
Thank you.

15:50.650 --> 15:53.949
Would you like some...

